</li></ul></li></ul></li><li id="tree_64121327" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64121327" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64121327" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64121327" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64121327" name="comment_link_64121327" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23178067&amp;cid=64121327" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64121327)" >2003 is the year climate for 2023 was decided</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64121327" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64121327); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~sonlas">sonlas</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~sonlas">( 10282912 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64121327">		
		on Monday January 01, 2024 @06:58AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23178067&amp;cid=64121327">#64121327</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64121327"><p>Given the current amount of CO2 already in the atmosphere, the amount of CO2 we are still emitting today, and the stability of CO2 in the atmosphere, any change we do now will have an impact in ~20 years. This is why every IPCC scenario is the same for the next 20 years: it only starts to diverge (toward +1.5, or +2 or +3 or +4) after that point.</p><p>Which means the acceleration we are seeing now is due to what was emitted in 2003 and onward. This is not really news then. If we start counting what happened in 2003 as news, we might as well talk about the Pentium 4.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64121327">
