	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64121625"><p>So you topped caring about what the science had to say in the early 1980's? You heard one thing then so that's whats happening for the rest of time.</p><p>What's funny about the acid rain example is that most people actually got on board about the problem <i>and actually did something about it</i> and it mostly worked! (<a href="https://www.epa.gov/acidrain/acid-rain-program-results" title="epa.gov">Acid Rain Program Results</a> [epa.gov])</p><p>So from your own example "fuck it" isn't really viable nor true, it's just ideological nihilism.</p><p>Also the actual scientists (no disrespect to Leonard Nimoy) since the time you were both in fact in school were making pretty accurate predictions even since the 1970's about the warming factor</p><p><a href="https://eps.harvard.edu/files/eps/files/hausfather_2020_evaluating_historical_gmst_projections.pdf" title="harvard.edu">Evaluating the Performance of Past Climate Model Projections</a> [harvard.edu]</p><p>You were given wrong info as a toddler and the fact that you take your vague toddler recollections as accurate scientific consensus over say, the actual scientific consensus is a little less than convincing.</p></div>
	</div>

